# ==============================================================================
# Contested Ground: Code Repository
# ==============================================================================
#
# This repository contains the computational code for:
#
# xxx (xxxx). "xxx." xxx. xxx
#
# Overview
# --------
# This code implements a text-agnostic instrument for locating discursive
# tension within a single literary work. The "contested ground" framework
# learns a text's own internal registers from word company alone, builds a
# recursive taxonomy of words used alike, and then measures, at every
# branching, how far individual words are pulled between rival registers. Each
# branching must beat randomised rivals to exist, and each contestation score
# is calibrated against random re-dealings of the children among the parent's
# words, so the reading rests on the text's own structure rather than on
# imposed categories. A univocal text yields no branchings, and the report
# says so. The final test is the concordance, not the q-value.
#
# How the instrument works, in plain terms:
#  1. It keeps a text's content words.
#  2. It learns which words keep company with which above chance (PPMI), and
#     from that which words are used alike (those that keep company with the
#     same crowd).
#  3. It builds the text's taxonomy: communities of words used alike, found
#     recursively, where every branching must beat randomised rivals to exist.
#  4. At every branching it scores each parent word for how it divides between
#     the children, as even x exclusive x divide (each factor in 0..1):
#       even      leans on its top two children evenly
#       exclusive leans on those two only (when there are three or more)
#       divide    those two children are genuinely different ways of speaking
#  5. It calibrates every score against random re-dealings of the children
#     among the parent's words and prints concordance lines.
#
# Sections
# --------
#  1. Setup and Configuration
#  2. Load Required Libraries
#  3. The Instrument — Helper Functions
#  4. The Instrument — Contestation Analysis
#  5. Application to Text — Annotation and Run
#
# Sections 3 and 4 define the instrument as a text-agnostic function that takes
# any token stream. Section 5 loads and annotates a real text and runs the
# instrument on it. This separation keeps the instrument testable: a companion
# validation suite can load the instrument with RUN_TEXT set to FALSE and run
# it on synthetic texts with planted tensions and on shuffled controls.
#
# Key Functions
# -------------
#   knee_index()           - Parameter-free elbow detector, used to read the
#                            vocabulary floor off the frequency curve
#   knn_graph()            - Builds a mutual k-NN graph on a similarity
#                            submatrix, with sqrt(n) neighbours chosen locally
#   score_node()           - Scores every parent word at one branching for how
#                            it divides between the children
#   run_contested_ground() - The instrument: takes an annotated token stream
#                            and returns the taxonomy, scores, and report
#
# Requirements
# ------------
# R Version:
#   Code was developed using R version 4.2.3 "Shortstop Beagle".
#   May require adjustments for other R versions.
#
# Required R Packages:
#   Matrix      Sparse matrix operations
#   igraph      Network construction and community detection
#   dplyr       Data manipulation
#   tidyr       Data reshaping
